Bring a large #pot of salted water to a boil.

Roughly chop @sun-dried tomatoes{1.5%ounce}.

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Reserve 3⁄4 cup pasta cooking
water, then drain.

While spaghetti cooks, in a large #bowl, gently combine @ground beef{10%ounce},
@panko breadcrumbs{1/4%cup}, half the @garlic powder{1%teaspoon},
half the @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon}, and 1⁄2 tsp @salt{1/2%tsp}. (You'll
use the rest of the garlic powder and Italian seasoning later.)

Form into 10-12 11⁄2-inch meatballs.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large #pan over medium-high heat.
Add meatballs and cook, turning occasionally, until browned all over and mostly
cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.

Reduce heat to medium and stir in sun-dried tomatoes, @cream sauce base{4%ounce},
remaining garlic powder, remaining Italian seasoning, and 1⁄2 cup reserved pasta
cooking water. Bring to a simmer, then reduce heat to low. Cover and cook,
stirring occasionally, until meatballs are coated and cooked through,
~{5%minutes}.

> Ladle pasta cooking water directly from pot if pasta is not done yet.

Stir in drained spaghetti and toss to combine. Taste and season with salt and
@pepper{} if desired.

> If pasta seems dry, add splashes of pasta cooking water until everything is
> coated in a creamy sauce.

Divide spaghetti and meatballs between shallow #bowls. Top with
@Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon}(shredded) and serve.

> Ground Meat is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.